ays 13 and 14","Days 6 and 7","Days 11 and 12","Days 12 and 13"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe process of implantation follows a specific timeline:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDays \u003Cstrong\u003E6 and 7\u003C/strong\u003E: Initial blastocyst attachment and invasion begins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDays \u003Cstrong\u003E8 and 9\u003C/strong\u003E: Syncytiotrophoblast erosion of maternal vessels occurs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDays \u003Cstrong\u003E11 and 12\u003C/strong\u003E: Continued trophoblast development\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDays \u003Cstrong\u003E12 and 13\u003C/strong\u003E: Further lacunar network development\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDays \u003Cstrong\u003E13 and 14\u003C/strong\u003E: Primary villi formation begins, representing the next major developmental step after vessel erosion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrimary villi formation is crucial for early placental development and marks the beginning of specialised structures that will eventually form the definitive placenta.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Implantation begins around day 6-7 post-fertilisation with blastocyst attachment to the endometrium","The syncytiotrophoblast erodes maternal blood vessels around days 8-9 post-fertilisation","Primary villi formation occurs around days 13-14 post-fertilisation as the next major step in placental development"],"references":["Kim SM, Kim JS. A Review of Mechanisms of Implantation. Dev Reprod. 2017 Dec;21(4):351-359. doi: 10.12717/DR.2017.21.4.351. Epub 2017 Dec 31. PMID: 29359200; PMCID: PMC5769129","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57521"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15886"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57521"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:02:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:04:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8577"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72051"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Reproductive System (Female)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data"